<emphasis id="218AF01ABE79FFA1FE97DA9DFE3DF8A4" bold="true" box="[264,447,1784,1808]" pageId="3" pageNumber="30">FIGURES 7–9.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="D4FE578BBE79FFA1FE50DA9CFC80F8A4" authority="Maia &amp; Fernandes, 2005" authorityName="Maia &amp; Fernandes" authorityYear="2005" box="[463,770,1785,1808]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Asphondylia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="microcapillata" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE79FFA1FE50DA9CFC80F8A4" box="[463,770,1785,1808]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="30">Asphondylia microcapillata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="3AB94D61BE79FFA1FC8CDA9CFCD4F8A4" box="[787,854,1785,1808]" pageId="3" pageNumber="30" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE79FFA1FCF8DA9DFCF9F8A4" bold="true" box="[871,891,1784,1808]" pageId="3" pageNumber="30">7.</emphasis>
Male abdominal segment 3 to end (dorsolateral). 
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE79FFA1FE3ADB7EFE38F887" bold="true" box="[421,442,1819,1843]" pageId="3" pageNumber="30">8.</emphasis>
Female abdominal segment 5 to end (dorsolateral). 
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE79FFA1FC7ADB7EFC7AF887" bold="true" box="[997,1016,1819,1843]" pageId="3" pageNumber="30">9.</emphasis>
Male terminalia (dorsal).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="13412C08BE7EFFA6FEA7DD79FC34FE62" blockId="4.[264,1325,284,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">
Thorax: Anepimeron setose, other pleural sclerites asetose. Wing length (from arculus to apex): 
<quantity id="D40681EDBE7EFFA6FEE8DD21FD86FEEA" box="[375,516,324,350]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.3" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="2.4" valueMax="2.5" valueMin="2.3">2.3–2.5 mm</quantity>
in male (
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE7EFFA6FDEBDD21FD01FEE9" box="[628,643,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5); 
<quantity id="D40681EDBE7EFFA6FD55DD21FCD5FEEA" box="[714,855,324,350]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" metricValueMax="2.9" metricValueMin="1.9" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="2.4" valueMax="2.9" valueMin="1.9">1.9–2.9 mm</quantity>
in female (
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE7EFFA6FC42DD21FC6EFEE9" box="[989,1004,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5). First tarsomeres with apical spur 
<quantity id="D40681EDBE7EFFA6FE10DD09FDCBFE32" box="[399,585,364,390]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.75" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="0.0275" valueMax="0.03" valueMin="0.025">0.025–0.03 mm</quantity>
long in male (
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE7EFFA6FD6CDD09FC80FE31" box="[755,770,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5), 
<quantity id="D40681EDBE7EFFA6FCD7DD09FC3DFE32" box="[840,959,364,390]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="0.035">0.035 mm</quantity>
in female (
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE7EFFA6FBDBDD09FBD1FE31" box="[1092,1107,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 2). Tarsal claws simple, robust and strongly curved near midlength, similar in shape on 3 pairs of legs; empodia well developed, as long as bend in claws (
<figureCitation id="8BC5308DBE7EFFA6FCFFDDD9FC25FE62" box="[864,935,444,470]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[264,382,1798,1822]" captionTargetBox="[280,1298,389,1750]" captionTargetId="figure-56@2.[261,1326,369,1772]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 1. Male head (frontal). 2. Female head (frontal). 3. Male antennal flagellomeres 9­12. 4. Male antennal flagellomere 5. 5. Female antennal flagellomere 5. 6. Female, midtarsal claw and empodium (lateral)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051079" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051079/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="13412C08BE7EFFA6FEA7DD81FD7EFCA2" blockId="4.[264,1325,284,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">
Abdomen. Male (
<figureCitation id="8BC5308DBE7EFFA6FD8EDD81FDE2FE4A" box="[529,608,484,510]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="3.[264,382,1784,1808]" captionTargetBox="[444,1124,715,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-164@3.[423,1163,700,1759]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 7. Male abdominal segment 3 to end (dorsolateral). 8. Female abdominal segment 5 to end (dorsolateral). 9. Male terminalia (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051083/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
): tergites 1–7 rectangular with complete row of posterior setae, several lateral setae, 2 basal trichoid sensilla and elsewhere with scattered scales. Tergite 8 constricted mesally with only 2 trichoid sensilla as vestiture. Sternites 2–7 rectangular with setae more abundant at midlength, complete row of posterior setae and 2 basal trichoid sensilla; sternite 8 ovoid with several scattered setae and 2 basal trichoid sensilla. Female (
<figureCitation id="8BC5308DBE7EFFA6FE47DEC9FDA3FD72" box="[472,545,684,710]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="3.[264,382,1784,1808]" captionTargetBox="[444,1124,715,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-164@3.[423,1163,700,1759]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 7. Male abdominal segment 3 to end (dorsolateral). 8. Female abdominal segment 5 to end (dorsolateral). 9. Male terminalia (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051083/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
): tergites 1–7 as in male. Tergite 8 notched laterally with 2 basal trichoid sensilla. Sternites 2–6 as in male. Sternite 7 with scattered setae and 2 basal trichoid sensilla. Sternite 8 not sclerotized.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="13412C08BE7EFFA6FEA7DF41FD5DFC02" blockId="4.[264,1325,284,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">
Male terminalia (
<figureCitation id="8BC5308DBE7EFFA6FD97DF41FDD1FC8A" box="[520,595,804,830]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="3.[264,382,1784,1808]" captionTargetBox="[444,1124,715,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-164@3.[423,1163,700,1759]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 7. Male abdominal segment 3 to end (dorsolateral). 8. Female abdominal segment 5 to end (dorsolateral). 9. Male terminalia (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051083/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
): gonocoxites wide and setose; gonostylus short, ovoid, and setose, with 2 sclerotized teeth; cercus reniform, completely separate and setose; hypoproct sligthly bilobed and setose; parameres absent; aedeagus triangular, tapering gradually toward apex, pointed apically.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="13412C08BE7EFFA6FEA7DFA1FEDDFBB2" blockId="4.[264,1325,284,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">
Ovipositor (
<figureCitation id="8BC5308DBE7EFFA6FE5ADFA1FD89FC6A" box="[453,523,964,990]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="3.[264,382,1784,1808]" captionTargetBox="[444,1124,715,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-164@3.[423,1163,700,1759]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 7. Male abdominal segment 3 to end (dorsolateral). 8. Female abdominal segment 5 to end (dorsolateral). 9. Male terminalia (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051083/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) protrusible and needlelike, needle part 1.7–2.2 as long as sternite 7 (
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE7EFFA6FE8DDF89FEA3FBB1" box="[274,289,1004,1029]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 4).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="13412C08BE7EFFA6FEA7D871FC4DFAF2" blockId="4.[264,1325,284,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE7EFFA6FEA7D871FE02FB9A" bold="true" box="[312,384,1044,1070]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Pupa.</emphasis>
Color: brownish. Length: 
<quantity id="D40681EDBE7EFFA6FD21D871FCD9FB9A" box="[702,859,1044,1070]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8249999999999997" metricValueMax="4.1" metricValueMin="3.55" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="3.8249999999999997" valueMax="4.1" valueMin="3.55">3.55–4.1 mm</quantity>
(
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE7EFFA6FCF1D871FCFFFB99" box="[878,893,1044,1069]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5). Head (
<figureCitation id="8BC5308DBE7EFFA6FB87D871FBF3FB9A" box="[1048,1137,1044,1070]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1806,1830]" captionTargetBox="[305,1269,400,1759]" captionTargetId="figure-76@5.[289,1277,393,1772]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 10. Pupal head (frontal). 11. Pupal prothoracic spiracle. 12. Pupal terminal segments (dorsal). 13. Larval spatula and associated papillae. 14. Larval terminal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051085" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051085/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
): antennal horn triangular, long (
<quantity id="D40681EDBE7EFFA6FE53D859FDF9FBE2" box="[460,635,1084,1110]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.95" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="0.195" valueMax="0.23" valueMin="0.16">0.16–0.23 mm</quantity>
, 
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE7EFFA6FD17D859FD15FBE1" box="[648,663,1084,1109]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5), with serrated margin; cephalic seta 
<quantity id="D40681EDBE7EFFA6FB1FD859FAA9FBE2" box="[1152,1323,1084,1110]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="7" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="0.055" valueMax="0.07" valueMin="0.04">0.04–0.07 mm</quantity>
long (
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE7EFFA6FECED801FEE2FBC9" box="[337,352,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5); upper frontal horns bilobed (length: 
<quantity id="D40681EDBE7EFFA6FCF1D801FC5FFBCA" box="[878,989,1124,1150]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="0.01">0.01 mm</quantity>
, 
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE7EFFA6FC72D801FC7EFBC9" box="[1005,1020,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5); lower frontal horn absent; 2 pairs of lower facial papillae (1 pair asetose, other pair with seta 
<quantity id="D40681EDBE7EFFA6FBE0D8E9FAA9FB12" box="[1151,1323,1164,1190]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="0.015" valueMax="0.02" valueMin="0.01">0.01–0.02 mm</quantity>
long, 
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE7EFFA6FED3D8D1FED9FB79" box="[332,347,1204,1229]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5); 3 pairs of lateral facial papillae (1 pair with seta 
<quantity id="D40681EDBE7EFFA6FC75D8D1FB26FB7A" box="[1002,1188,1204,1230]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="0.0175" valueMax="0.02" valueMin="0.015">0.015–0.02 mm</quantity>
long and 2 pairs asetose). Upper cephalic margin thickened laterally. Thorax: prothoracic spiracle setiform, elongate and curved, 
<quantity id="D40681EDBE7EFFA6FDE6D961FCA6FAAA" box="[633,804,1284,1310]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7999999999999998" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="0.18" valueMax="0.2" valueMin="0.16">0.16–0.20 mm</quantity>
long (
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE7EFFA6FCEBD961FC01FAA9" box="[884,899,1284,1309]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5) (
<figureCitation id="8BC5308DBE7EFFA6FC50D961FBA5FAAA" box="[975,1063,1284,1310]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1806,1830]" captionTargetBox="[305,1269,400,1759]" captionTargetId="figure-76@5.[289,1277,393,1772]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 10. Pupal head (frontal). 11. Pupal prothoracic spiracle. 12. Pupal terminal segments (dorsal). 13. Larval spatula and associated papillae. 14. Larval terminal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051085" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051085/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Abdomen (
<figureCitation id="8BC5308DBE7EFFA6FB5CD961FA9EFAAA" box="[1219,1308,1284,1310]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1806,1830]" captionTargetBox="[305,1269,400,1759]" captionTargetId="figure-76@5.[289,1277,393,1772]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 10. Pupal head (frontal). 11. Pupal prothoracic spiracle. 12. Pupal terminal segments (dorsal). 13. Larval spatula and associated papillae. 14. Larval terminal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051085" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051085/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
): segments 2–9 with transverse rows of crescent dorsal spines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="13412C08BE7EFFA6FEA7D931FDC1F9BA" blockId="4.[264,1325,284,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE7EFFA6FEA7D931FE09FADA" bold="true" box="[312,395,1364,1390]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Larva.</emphasis>
Body elongate, cylindrical, and tapered at both ends. Color: yellow. Length: 
<quantity id="D40681EDBE7EFFA6FE97D919FE14FA22" box="[264,406,1404,1430]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" metricValueMax="2.6" metricValueMin="1.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="2.2" valueMax="2.6" valueMin="1.8">1.8–2.6 mm</quantity>
(
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE7EFFA6FE38D919FE34FA21" box="[423,438,1404,1429]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5). Integument rough. Spatula with 2 well developed teeth and relatively short stalk; surrounding area not pigmented; sternal papillae setose; 4 setose lateral papillae on each side of spatula (
<figureCitation id="8BC5308DBE7EFFA6FD11D9A9FD5CFA52" box="[654,734,1484,1510]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1806,1830]" captionTargetBox="[305,1269,400,1759]" captionTargetId="figure-76@5.[289,1277,393,1772]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 10. Pupal head (frontal). 11. Pupal prothoracic spiracle. 12. Pupal terminal segments (dorsal). 13. Larval spatula and associated papillae. 14. Larval terminal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051085" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051085/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig.13</figureCitation>
). Terminal segment short, convex, with 4 pairs of terminal papillae (
<figureCitation id="8BC5308DBE7EFFA6FE41D991FDB7F9BA" box="[478,565,1524,1550]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1806,1830]" captionTargetBox="[305,1269,400,1759]" captionTargetId="figure-76@5.[289,1277,393,1772]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 10. Pupal head (frontal). 11. Pupal prothoracic spiracle. 12. Pupal terminal segments (dorsal). 13. Larval spatula and associated papillae. 14. Larval terminal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051085" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051085/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="13412C08BE7EFFA6FEA7DA79FC35F94A" blockId="4.[264,1325,284,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE7EFFA6FEA7DA79FEEFF982" bold="true" box="[312,365,1564,1590]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Gall</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="8BC5308DBE7EFFA6FEE1DA79FE54F982" box="[382,470,1564,1590]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="6.[264,368,1305,1329]" captionTargetBox="[281,1305,633,1294]" captionTargetId="figure-239@6.[281,1305,632,1296]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 15. Gall of Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. on Bauhinia brevipes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051089" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051089/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
). The spheroid leaf galls are covered with short, whitish trichomes. The gall is positioned between the adaxial leaf laminae and has a single chamber where a single galling larva is found. The two polar regions of the spheroid galls collapse the twolobed leaves of 
<emphasis id="218AF01ABE7EFFA6FE58DAF1FD24F919" box="[455,678,1684,1709]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">
<taxonomicName id="D4FE578BBE7EFFA6FE58DAF1FD20F919" box="[455,674,1684,1709]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Bauhinia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brevipes">Bauhinia brevipes</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
At the beginning of gall formation, the trichomes are whitish but may change color as the galls mature, and when exposed to direct sunlight may present reddish tones at the distal portion of the trichomes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
